article.description: Megan Ronhovde made all six of her 3-point shots in scoring a career-high 24 points, and Anne O'Neil missed a triple-double by one rebound for Iowa State (No. 18 ESPN/USA Today, No. 19 AP) in a 103-76 victory Wednesday night over Colorado.
article.headline: Ronhovde six-of-six from three-point range
article.linkText: O'Neil just misses triple-double in Iowa State rout
article.story:
AMES, Iowa (AP) -- Anne O'Neil decided she could wait for another
chance to reach a triple-double.

O'Neil fell one rebound short of becoming the first Iowa State
player with a triple-double, and Megan Ronhovde made all six of her
3-point shots in scoring a career-high 24 points, leading the
Cyclones (No. 18 ESPN/USA Today, No. 19 AP) to a 103-76 victory over Colorado on Wednesday
night.

O'Neil had 18 points, 10 assists and nine rebounds when she left
the game with 4:36 remaining. She did not return, though coach Bill
Fennelly gave her the option.

"When I took her out, my son, Billy, said, `Dad, she needs
another rebound to get a triple-double,' " Fennelly said. "I
asked Anne, `Do you want to go back in?' She said, `No, let the
other kids play. I'm done.'

"That's not just somebody who had a good game. That's someone
who's a leader who understands the big picture."

Fennelly then added, "I probably wouldn't have put her in
anyway, but I wanted to give her a chance to answer the question."

Iowa State (17-2, 7-1 Big 12) pulled into a tie with Texas Tech
for first place in the conference, scoring the most points in a
league game since a 112-79 victory over Baylor on Feb. 26, 2000.

"That was probably the most fun game we've played all year,"
Ronhovde said. "The crowd was into it, we were all into it. We had
played two road games and it was really fun to get back to
Hilton."

Colorado (8-11, 1-7) trailed just 53-45 with 17:30 remaining,
but Iowa State went on a 26-5 surge to break it open and eventually
led by as many as 31 points. Ronhovde hit two 3-pointers during the
big burst, while O'Neil, Mary Fox and Lyndsey Medders made one
each.

Jasmina Ilic went 6-for-12 from 3-point range and led Colorado
with 22 points and 10 rebounds. Kara Richards added 19 points for
the Buffaloes, who shot 36 percent in the first half and 39.7
percent for the game.

Lisa Kriener added a season-high 14 points for Iowa State, Katie
Robinette scored 13 and Fox 11. The Cyclones finished 15-for-28 on
3-pointers and shot 57.4 percent overall.

"Did they miss?" Colorado coach Ceal Barry said. "It seemed
like they made everything, especially in that first half. My team
is young and they're tired. They were a little overwhelmed by
everything."

O'Neil didn't shoot until making a fadeaway on the baseline 6½
minutes into the game, then went on to score 15 points in the first
half.

"I just kind of let the game come to me," she said. "I've
finally learned that my senior year. The flow of the game will
eventually come around to you."

Ronhovde made her first eight shots and her only miss was a
putback attempt from 2 feet. She hung the net on the rim by
swishing a 3-pointer midway through the second half, then brought
it back down 33 seconds later by swishing another 3.

Things went so well for the 6-foot-1 sophomore that even when it
appeared she would look bad, she still scored.

On a fast break during Iowa State's decisive run, Ronhovde was
running down the floor and didn't see the ball coming her way. But
it bounced right in front of her, she grabbed it and continued in
for a layup.

"Those are things you dream about and she had one of those
games tonight," Fennelly said.
